Analyze the following job description and extract structured signals a candidate would use to tailor their resume.

JD:
"""
{{ jd_text }}
"""

Return a single JSON object with this exact shape:

{
  "must_have": [
    {"tech": "<short name>", "category": "<see categories>", "evidence": "<short quote from JD>"}
  ],
  "nice_to_have": [
    {"tech": "<short name>", "category": "<see categories>"}
  ],
  "soft_skills": ["<short phrase>"],
  "domain_keywords": ["<short phrase>"],
  "seniority_level": "junior|mid|senior|staff|principal",
  "exact_phrases_to_mirror": ["<short phrase>"]
}

Categories (use one of):
  frontend, backend, cloud, db, data, ml, devops, mobile,
  language, framework, tool, methodology, security, streaming, other

Extraction rules:
- must_have: technologies, frameworks, languages, or experience the JD explicitly requires.
  Signals: "required", "must have", "X+ years of <tech>", "responsibilities include working with <tech>".
- nice_to_have: items marked as "preferred", "plus", "bonus", "nice to have".
- evidence: a short verbatim quote (≤ 15 words) from the JD that justifies the inclusion.
- soft_skills: only those explicitly named (e.g., "strong communication", "ownership"). Do not invent.
- domain_keywords: business / industry / domain terms (e.g., "real-time analytics",
  "event-driven architecture", "fintech", "developer productivity"). Not technologies.
- seniority_level: infer from years required, scope, title, and reporting depth.
- exact_phrases_to_mirror: 3-7 short, distinctive phrases from the JD that a resume
  could echo back to improve ATS keyword match. Prefer noun phrases.

Hard rules:
- Do not invent skills the JD does not mention.
- Do not include duplicates between must_have and nice_to_have.
- If a section has no items, return an empty list.
- Output the JSON object ONLY. No prose, no markdown fences, no comments.
